post_text:
The parents of 19 Broadmoor students were notified today that a school employee with whom they were in contact has tested positive for the Covid virus. In addition, the New Mexico Public Health Department was notified of the information.
The students - who were present in a classroom with the individual on one of four days this week - have been asked to quarantine. Several staff members will also self-isolate.
Broadmoor as well as the affected classroom will be sanitized and deep cleaned.
Because the remainder of Broadmoor students followed social distancing guidelines and were not in contact with the person, other classes are not affected. Broadmoor students - other than those who are quarantining - may attend school on their regular schedule beginning Monday.

UPDATE:
Per PED, Department of Health, and CDC guidelines, face shields will no longer be considered suitable face coverings when worn alone. HMS students or staff who wish to wear a face shield to school will also need to wear a mask.

In addition, the following face coverings are no longer CDC approved face coverings and will NOT be considered suitable masks for HMS students and staff going forward:

-Masks that have exhalation valves or vents
-Bandanas
-Scarves
-Neck Gaiters (also known as neck fleece)
-Face Shields

Thank you for your help in keeping all of our Hobbs families safe.

As a precaution, the parents of four Booker T. Washington students were notified today about a BTW teacher who exhibited symptoms of illness.
It should be noted that the teacher - who was in contact with two students on Wednesday and two on Thursday - reported symptoms on Thursday morning. The individual has NOT tested positive for Covid and was referred to a primary care physician.
The students have been asked to quarantine.
As an added precaution, four BTW staff members who also were in contact with the teacher are self-isolating. In addition, the affected BTW classroom was vacated and deep cleaned.
Because the remainder of BTW students followed social distancing guidelines and were not in contact with the teacher, other BTW classes were not affected. Classes will continue today and on Friday as scheduled.
It should be emphasized that the employee has NOT tested positive for the virus.

Chloe Chronis Fouts is at Ralph Tasker Arena.
September 8 at 3:22 PM · Instagram ·

If you know someone in need of groceries:
Hobbs High will be hosting our monthly Roadrunner Food Bank on Monday 9/14 at 3:00 pm at Tasker Arena.

•It will be a drive-through at Tasker Arena parking lot (No parking or even getting out of cars!)
• We will have 2 entrances open to Tasker parking lot to expedite waiting time - one behind the visitor stands of Watson & one by Tydings Auditorium.
•For your safety and ours we will not have to see photo IDs. There will be no transfer of paper or pens. We will only ask the driver for verbal count of adults, seniors & children living in the home for our report.
•We will serve by loading pre-boxed items into each vehicle’s trunk.
•All those serving will be wearing gloves and masks to ease the minds of our local families.
•We will have enough food for 100 families.

De acuerdo con el anuncio del Public Education Department (Departamento de Educación Pública) el jueves por la tarde, Hobbs Municipal Schools pospondrán el inicio híbrido del año escolar de la próxima semana para los estudiantes de la escuela primaria.
En cambio, Pre-K hasta tercer grado seguirá la escuela en persona 5: 1 programada instituida esta semana con los cambios que se indican a continuación para adaptarse al feriado de Labor Day. Las clases híbridas comenzarán en Hobbs cuando PED lo autorice, según el número de nuevos casos de COVID-19 diagnosticados en el condado de Lea.

post_text: A partir del viernes 4 de septiembre, HMS ofrecerá desayuno y comida gratis a todos los menores de 18 años. Los estudiantes ya no necesitan presentar su identificación o número de identificación y no necesitan ser estudiantes registrados para recibir una comida. Los padres pueden recoger las comidas para sus hijos. "Nuestro objetivo siempre ha sido alimentar a los niños de Hobbs, y ahora, con la nueva orientación del USDA, podemos hacer precisamente eso", dijo la gerente de Nutritional Cervices, Sonya Moore. Las comidas se pueden recoger en todas las escuelas excepto en Highland. Ese vecindario es atendido por Coronado Elementary. Nueve rutas de autobús también entregan comidas a los lugares que se enumeran a continuación.

post_text: As of today, HMS will offer free breakfast and lunch to anyone 18 and under. Students no longer need to present their id or id number and need not be a registered student to receive a meal. Parents may pick up meals for their children. "It has always been our goal to feed the children of Hobbs, and now with new guidance from the USDA we are able to do just that," Nutrtion Services Manager Sonya Moore said. Meals can be picked up at every school except Highland. That neighborhood is serviced by Coronado Elementary. Nine bus routes also deliver meals to the locations listed below.

Three new groups of five students each will continue to return to the classroom on Tuesday, Thursday and Friday as HMS follows Public Education Department guidelines for re-entry.

Three new groups of five students each will continue to return to the classroom on Tuesday, Thursday and Friday as HMS follows Public Education Department guidelines for re-entry.

post_text: Although the Public Education Department will re-evaluate its decision on Wednesday, PED has notified HMS that it will not be able to begin in-person Hybrid classes on a large-scale basis as planned on Sept. 8. Hobbs (and Lea County) will not be authorized to do so until the Covid positivity test rate falls below 5 percent. Instead, HMS will continue the schedule implemented this week of 5-1 teacher-student ratio for students in grades Pre-K through third. Because there is no school next Monday, students who attend on that day this week will move to Tuesday next week, Tuesday will move to Wednesday and Thursday and Friday students will remain on the same schedule.

post_text:
HMS is partnering with Studer Education to create a new strategic plan for the district. The strategic plan will define what success looks like and what the goals will be for the district in the next 5 years. HMS and Studer Education will seek input from various stakeholders in the community including parents, HMS employees, community partners, and community members.

Assisting HMS in creating the 2020-2025 strategic plan is Dr. Gayle Juneau-Butler. As a Leader Coach at Studer Education, Dr. Juneau-Butler has spent her career impacting student success for education institutions. Dr. Juneau-Butler will be scheduling meetings with the purpose of gaining insight and input from community members. If you are interested in participating please contact Dr. Juneau-Butler at gayle.juneaubutler@studereducation.com

#thehobbsway #wearehobbs

HMS computer technicians will be at the HMS Training Center from 9 a.m.-1 p.m. today to hand out devices and to answer questions for students who received HMS laptops and are having issues.

Parents, remember that one device will be issued to every two children in kindergarten through 12th grade. Devices will be released only to the guardian listed in Skyward. (We cannot issue devices to students, non-guardians, or emergency contacts).

In order to receive a laptop, your child must be fully registered AND you must have selected that you want Hobbs Schools to issue a device. (If you did not take this step when registering online, please contact your child’s school to make that change).

Finally, you must wear a mask and you must bring a photo ID for verification. #thehobbsway

post_text: Anybody interested in making a donation of household goods or clothing to help a Hobbs family devastated by a lightning-ignited fire can do so at Coronado Elementary until 2 p.m. Friday and next week during school hours. (Please, no cash donations). The family - which includes a kindergartner girl (size 5T) and HHS senior boy - lost most of their belongings in the fire that sent a bolt of lightning through all electrical appliances early Friday morning and burned the kindergartner's bedroom. Coronado teacher Bekim Kjermi, who lives across the street, ran through the powerful thunderstorm in bare feet amid downed power lines to bang on the door and alert the family. Although there were no injuries, the family lost most of their belongings.

post_text: As the orientation process for the complex start of a new school year began Wednesday, parents and their children showed up in person or engaged in zoom conferences to learn the basics of how the 2020-21 school year will start. In some places, such as the Freshman High School, cars lined up for a “drive-by orientation” that included parents receiving packets containing their students’ ID cards and first week of homework. School officially begins on Monday with “packet” handouts that will be graded, then moves into an online phase on Aug. 17 before face-to-face instruction starts for elementary students on Sept. 8. Orientation sessions will continue through Friday.

post_text: As the number of Covid-19 cases fluctuate statewide, HMS will use the following learning models. The district begins the school year on Aug. 5 using the Hybrid model (yellow). The goal is to move to the Traditional model (green) as soon as it is safe for students and staff. In the event of another school closure order from the New Mexico Public Education Department, HMS will revert to the Remote model (red). HOLA (white) will be available throughout the school year regardless of Covid numbers.

The New Mexico Department of Health announced in January that it will mandate the HPV vaccine for school attendance in the 2021-22 school year.

Please be advised that this mandate will be enforced in August 2021. If the mandate is not repealed, parents who DO NOT want their child to receive the vaccine can file for an exemption each school year. More details on the vaccine and exemption will be available as the implementation date approaches next summer. In the meantime, here is a link to the exemption form (which does not yet include HPV vaccine because it is not required until 2021): https://www.nmhealth.org/publication/view/form/454/

Hobbs High School Announcements
May 20 at 9:25 PM ·

Mr. Kaney had the pleasure of awarding this young man with the Principal’s leadership award this evening at his home. We would typically do this at an awards assembly with almost 2000 students involved. Everything’s just different. Regardless of the setting, Keaton Hartman was very worthy of this award. The picture itself is during a state semifinal game. He could have used his opponents weakness to take advantage, instead... he helped stretch out a cramping opponent. His willingness to be humbled and serve others was just one of his examples of leadership I witnessed throughout the year. Go Eagles!🦅

Dear Parents,

Thank you for your partnership and support, especially through this difficult time. As we prepare for the start of school in August 2020, we would like to get your input on how we begin the school year. We will request additional surveys throughout the summer as our views may change with time. The Department of Health as well as the Governor will dictate some of our options, but we want to hear your voice. Please use the following link to begin the "Parent Survey-Opening School 2020."

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/QHLLM5M

Thank you and have a wonderful day!

TJ Parks

Superintendent

Hobbs Municipal School

post_text:
Video marquee signs and stadiums around Hobbs will light up on Monday night in honor of Hobbs High School’s 2020 graduates.

Beginning at 7 p.m. on Monday - the same date and time that commencement was originally scheduled prior to the Covid-19 lockdown - lights will be turned on at Watson Stadium, Tasker Arena, Tydings Auditorium, Rockwind Golf Course, CORE and Veterans Memorial Stadium. The City of Hobbs and Lea County is joining HMS in the #LighttheNight enterprise.

In addition, display boards at each sports facility, (which will be locked to the public to prevent large gatherings), will also project a slideshow of senior photos featuring our nearly 600 graduates.

Kasis Enterprises has donated use of four video boards around the city and will likewise run the slideshow of senior photos from 7-10 p.m on Monday night.

New Mexico Junior College's Channel 19 on cable TV will also loop the senior video slideshow from 7-9 p.m. on Monday.

Please join us in honoring these students by turning a light on Monday as we #LighttheNight.

post_text: Acaban de informarle a nuestro distrito escolar que alguno de nuestros empleados de HMS quien ayudo a distribuir lonches la semana pasada en la escuela Booker T. Washington estuvo en contacto recientemente con una persona a cual dio positivo a la prueba del COVID19 virus. Cuando la empleada de HMS fue probada el lunes, los resultados dieron negativo. Sin embargo por precaución, la escuela Booker T. Washington permanecerá cerrada a todo personal para volver a ser desinfectada. Adicionalmente, la distribución de lonches sera afuera de la escuela por el momento. HMS continuará a tener la comunidad al tanto de todo a como recibimos la información. post_text:
Our district has been informed that an HMS employee who helped distribute lunches last week at Booker T. Washington was recently in contact with a person who tested positive for the Covid 19 virus. When the HMS employee was tested for the virus on Monday, the results were negative.
In an abundance of caution, however, the Booker T. Washington campus is closed to all staff and will be resanitized. In addition, Distribution of meals - which are prepared at the Central Kitchen away from the BTW campus - will occur at the regular time outside the BTW building for the time being.

Hobbs High School Announcements
March 31 at 6:25 PM ·

The testing center at NMJC is currently closed, and they currently do not have a date to reopen for Accuplacer testing. Likewise, we are not allowed to test on HHS campus. I have been in contact with the Vice President of New Mexico Junior College, and we are working on a plan to insure that students get an equitable opportunity to apply for Hobbs Dual Credit Academy (early college). Hopefully, we will have a plan in place about requirements for acceptance and application due dates and instructions for turning those applications early next week. As soon as I get clear direction, I will send it out via School Messenger and post it on our school website and announcement page. Enrollment at NMJC has also been postponed until later this semester, so no one is being left out or not being given the opportunity to apply. Thanks for your patience as we sort through this process. It is a learning curve for us all.

Please email Yvonne Carpenter, carpentery@hobbsschools.net for further questions.

We would like to share information provided during the governor’s press conference Friday morning.
The Public Education Department will waive its instructional hours requirement so that school days missed during the coming three weeks of state mandated closure will not need to be made up this summer. Anybody with a health related question should call 1-855-600-3453. Health care experts will be available to answer concerns. Anyone with questions related to child care or family support should call 1-833-551-0518.

HMS gustaría anunciar los siguientes planes para la alimentación de nuestros estudiantes durante las próximas tres semanas en las que se cerrará la escuela:

El desayuno y la comida estarán disponibles de forma gratuita para todos los estudiantes de HMS (pre-K hasta el grado 12) en cada escuela primaria de lunes a viernes. (Escuelas secundarias no serán sitios de comida, pero todos los estudiantes serán elegibles para alimentos.)

Comidas para llevar estarán disponibles desde las 7:30 am hasta las 8:15 am cada mañana. Habrá comida de las 11:30-12:30. Las comidas serán para recoger solamente.
Más información se proporcionará como el distrito sigue haciendo planes para el cierre de las escuelas inesperado.

post_text:
HMS would like to announce the following plans for feeding our students during the coming three weeks in which school will be closed:

Breakfast and lunch will be available free of charge for all HMS students (pre-K through 12th grade) at each elementary school Monday through Friday. (Secondary schools will not be meal sites but all students will be eligible for food.)

Packaged meals will be available from 7:30 a.m. until 8:15 a.m. each morning. Lunch will be provided from 11:30 p.m. to 12:30 p.m. The meals will be for pick up only.
More information will be provided as the district continues to make plans for the unexpected school closure.

New Mexico state health officials with the New Mexico Department of Health have announced this evening that a fourth New Mexico resident has tested presumptive positive for COVID-19, adding to the three presumptive positive tests from earlier in the day. This new case is also travel-related.

post_text: Jeff Taylor got his start playing basketball in Hobbs. A member of the mid 1970s Tasker teams, he went on to play for Texas Tech, the Houston Rockets and overseas. He eventually settled in Sweden where he raised a family - including a son, Jeff Taylor Jr., who helped the Eagles win a state championship in 2008. The elder Taylor passed away earlier this week in Sweden. Condolences go out to the Taylor family from the Eagle Nation near and far.

post_text: While BTW Elementary has been studying famous figures in Black history this month, Wednesday morning was dedicated to honoring Hobbs native Pat Jones. Jones, a Hobbs School Board member and former city commissioner, made state history when she became the first Black woman elected to public office in 1989. She talked to students about growing up in Hobbs, attending Edison, working at BTW and eventually GTE - then encouraged them to read often and set goals. BTW Principal Robert Sims Jr. said a hall will be named in her honor at the school.

post_text: Tuesday night's Roswell win makes it 18 district titles in a row for Lady Eagles Coach Joey Carpenter - who coached at Roswell before taking over head coach duties at Hobbs four years ago. shared_text:
Brenda Hightower Wilson is with Jason Parrish and 2 others.
February 8 at 6:19 PM ·

Hobbs Eagle swimmers —District Champs! Eagle Dive-Dist Champs!
We had a lot of kids qualify for state in their individual events:
Nolan Kuykendall: 200 free,
Sebastian Blevins: 200 IM &100 breaststroke
Kason Bowman: 50 freestyle & 100 freestyle,
Molly Moody 100 freestyle.
We previously qualified three relays: 200 Medley, 200 free, and 400 free.
Great job Eagles and coaches! #theGoldStandard
